-- Thailand Stocks: BEC, Precious Shipping, Robinson, Thai Airways
-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 2012-03-16T09:47:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-03-16/thailand-stock-movers-precious-shipping-city-steel-robinson.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  Thailand   trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the close in Bangkok.  The SET Index rose 1.6 percent to 1,189.56, the highest
close since July 1996. The gauge climbed 2.7 percent this week,
the biggest weekly advance in three months.  Bulk shipping companies:  Precious Shipping Pcl (PSL)  ,
Thailand’s biggest operator of commodity carriers, increased 1.2
percent to 16.30 baht, the steepest advance since Feb. 29.
 Thoresen Thai Agencies Pcl (TTA)   added 1.5 percent to 20.2
baht.  The Baltic Dry Index, a measure of shipping costs for dry-
bulk commodities, climbed 1.3 percent yesterday, its 16th day of
gains, according to the Baltic Exchange in London. That’s the
highest level since Jan. 19.  BEC World Pcl (BEC)  , Thailand’s biggest television
broadcaster, jumped 5.2 percent to a record 51 baht. Investors
are speculating the company’s advertising revenue will increase
in 2012 as domestic spending rebounds in Thailand and it
broadcasts the Euro 2012 soccer tournament, Jitra Amornthum,
head of research at Finansia Syrus Securities Pcl, said by phone
today. Chatchai Thiamtong, BEC World’s chief financial officer,
wasn’t immediately available for comment when called at his
office.  City Steel Pcl (CITY)  , a producer of steel products,
surged 13 percent to 2.34 baht, the highest close since June
2008. Net income in the second quarter climbed 80 percent from a
year earlier to 39.8 million baht ($1.3 million).  Robinson Department Store Pcl (ROBINS)  , a department
store operator, gained 3 percent to 51.25 baht, the highest
close since Nov. 1996. The company plans to invest 2.8 billion
baht in 2012 to build three new stores, the English-language
Bangkok Post reported, citing Jiraphan Thongton, the company’s
general manager for finance. Jiraphan was not immediately
available for comment after a call to the office.  Thai Airways International Pcl (THAI)  , the country’s
largest carrier, advanced 2.4 percent to 25.50 baht. The carrier
filled 79 percent of its passenger seats in February, compared
with 77.6 percent in the same period last year, it said in a
statement today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
